Secretary of State to report on building stock
	The Secretary of State must—
		for the period of two years beginning with the commencement of thissection, and
		for each succeeding period of two years,
			prepare a report on progress during the period in connection with the purposesmentioned in section 1(1)(b) to (e) of the Building Act 1984 in the context ofthe building stock in England and Wales.
	A report under this section must (in particular) deal with—
		building regulations made during the period for any of those purposes;
		proposals current at the end of the period to make building regulations forany of those purposes;
		effects or likely effects of regulations or proposals dealt with in thereport under paragraphs (a) and (b);
		proposals considered by the Secretary of State during the period for thesetting of targets for any of those purposes in relation to—
		buildings in England and Wales; or
		services, fittings or equipment provided in or in connection with suchbuildings;
		overall changes during the period in—
		the efficiency with which energy is used in buildings in England and Wales;
		levels of emissions from such buildings that are emissions considered bythe Secretary of State to contribute to climate change;
		the extent to which such buildings have their own facilities forgenerating energy;
		the extent to which materials used in constructing, or carrying out worksin relation to, such buildings are recycled or re-used materials.
	A report under this section must contain an estimate, as at the end of theperiod, of the number of dwellings in England and Wales.
	The Secretary of State must lay before Parliament each report he preparesunder this section.

Registers of information and documents to be kept by local authorities
	After section 91 of the Building Act [1984 (c.55)](/id/ukpga/1984/55?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") insert—
	“91ARegisters to be kept by local authorities
		A local authority shall keep in a register such information and documentsas may be prescribed in connection with their functions, powers and dutiesconferred or imposed by or under this Act.
		The information and documents that may be prescribed for the purposes ofsubsection (1) above include, in particular—
			documents that are given or issued to, or deposited with, a local authorityin accordance with provision made by or under this Act, or copies of suchdocuments;
			copies of documents that are given, made or issued by a local authority inaccordance with provision so made;
			information with respect to documents of the kind mentioned in paragraph(a) or (b);
			information with respect to matters to which such documents relate.
		Information and documents that are required to be kept in a register undersubsection (1) above shall be so kept for the prescribed period.
		A local authority—
			shall maintain the register required under subsection (1) above in theprescribed manner;
			shall ensure that the register is available for inspection by members ofthe public during prescribed periods;
			shall, in prescribed circumstances, provide to members of the public, onrequest, copies of information and documents kept in the register;
			may, in prescribed circumstances, charge a member of the public to whomthey provide such copies a fee calculated in the prescribed manner.
		In this section—
			  * “documents” includes notices, certificates, orders, consents, demands and plans;
			  * “prescribed” means prescribed by regulations made by the Secretary of State under this section.
		Regulations under this section may—
			provide for a provision thereof to apply generally, or in a particulararea;
			make different provision for different areas and generally differentprovision for different circumstances or cases;
			include such supplemental, transitional and incidental provisions as appearto the Secretary of State to be expedient.
		The transitional provision that may be included in regulations under thissection includes transitional provision in relation to information that,immediately before the coming into force of the regulations, was contained inregisters kept by local authorities under section 56.
		The power to make regulations under this section is exercisable bystatutory instrument, which is subject to annulment in pursuance of aresolution of either House of Parliament.”
